By contrast, 1962-1966 (Classic Rock; British Invasion) contains many excellent, historically important tracks, but they are mostly early Beatles singles with straightforward arrangements and a consistent pop-rock approach. That makes it very enjoyable, especially for casual or nostalgic listening, but somewhat less likely to showcase the kinds of studio production detail and stylistic variety that a dedicated CD listener often relishes.
Therefore, based on the sole explicit preference (enjoying listening to CDs) and common-knowledge differences between the two collections, I select 1967-1970 The Blue Album for its richer production, broader stylistic range, and greater potential to reward attentive CD playback.

